e web |url=https://mclainfamilyband.com/discography |title=Vintage Recordings |author=The McLain Family Band |language=en |access-date=2020-01-10 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619090227/https://mclainfamilyband.com/discography |archive-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Morehead State University: RWM biography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moreheadstate.edu/content_template.aspx?id=12525&folderid=476 |title=Raymond W. McLain |publisher=[[Morehead State University]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502015514/http://www.moreheadstate.edu/content_template.aspx?id=12525&folderid=476 |archive-date=2016-05-02 |url-status=live |access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"Morehead State University: RMS biography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moreheadstate.edu/content_template.aspx?id=15407&folderid=476 |title=Ruth Smith |publisher=[[Morehead State University]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501202251/http://www.moreheadstate.edu/content_template.aspx?id=15407&folderid=476 |archive-date=2016-05-01 |url-status=live |access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"On the Road\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=On the Road |year= |type=[[Liner notes]] |publisher=Country Life Records |location=[[Berea, Kentucky]]}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\">{{cite web |url=http://www.symphonyofthemountains.org/Musicians/SymphonyoftheMountains/GuestArtists/TheMcLainFamilyBand/tabid/162/Default.aspx |title=The McLain Family Band |website=Symphony of the Mountains |language=en |access-date=2016-09-10 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428000328/http://www.symphonyofthemountains.org/Musicians/SymphonyoftheMountains/GuestArtists/TheMcLainFamilyBand/tabid/162/Default.aspx |archive-date=2009-04-28}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"Usborne Books & More\">{{cite web |url=http://usborneusa.com/home/story |title=Our Story |last1=Wartman |first1=Nancy Ann |website=Usborne Books & More |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322035921/http://usborneusa.com/home/story |archive-date=2016-03-22 |url-status=live |access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.mclainfamilyband.com/}}\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McLain Family Band, The}}\n[[Category:American bluegrass music groups]]\n[[Category:family musical groups]]\n[[Category:musical groups established in 1968]]\n[[Category:musical groups from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:people from Hindman, Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = The McLain Family Band\n| image           = McLain Family Band at the Carter Fold.jpg\n| alt             = Seven Caucasoid adults in semi-formal clothing are standing on a stage in front of a wooden sign that reads \"Carter Fold\".\n| caption         = At the [[Carter Family Fold]] on January 7, 2017\n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           = Bluegrass State\n| origin          = [[Hindman, Kentucky]], US\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]]\n* [[classical music|classical]] }}\n| years_active    = {{start date|1968}}\u2013present\n| label           = Country Life Records\n| associated_acts = {{plainlist|\n* The McLains\n* Michael and Jennifer McLain<!-- Band featuring Dan Kelly -->\n* Al, Alice & Ruth }}\n| website         = {{official website|1=https://mclainfamilyband.com}}\n| current_members = {{plainlist|\n* Raymond Winslow McLain\n* Alice McLain White\n* Al White\n* Ruth McLain Smith\n* Daxson Lewis\n* Nancy Ann Wartman\n* Michael McLain\n* Jennifer McLain }}\n| past_members    = {{plainlist|\n* Raymond Kane McLain\n* Michael Riopel\n* Beverly Buchanan\n* Tom Owen }}\n}}\n\n'''The McLain Family Band''' is an American [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] band founded in [[Hindman, Kentucky]] in 1968.\n\nRaymond Kane McLain studied folk music at university, and began playing bluegrass music with his then-three children in the late 1950s.  They formalized their group in 1968, and played for [[WYMT-TV#History|WKYH-TV]]  before moving to [[Berea, Kentucky]].  In the years since, the group has played in 50 [[U.S. state]]s, at renowned venues across the US, and on nationwide television.  Initially sponsored by the [[United States Department of State]], the McLains performed in 63 total nations.  From 1978\u20131987, the band hosted an annual family-friendly [[list of bluegrass music festivals|bluegrass festival]] in [[Bighill, Kentucky]].\n\nThe McLain Family Band developed their sound by ear, with naught but their patriarch having [[classically trained|classical training]].  [[Music review]]ers and [[ambassadors of the United States]] alike spoke of the band's authenticity and heartfelt approach to music.  In 2013, the [[International Bluegrass Music Association]] awarded the McLain Family Band with their Distinguished Achievement Award.\n\nSome McLain songs are originals, some are bluegrass and [[country music]] [[standard (music)|standards]], and some were specifically commissioned [[classical music|classical]] pieces: the first bluegrass band to combine those genres.  The core of the band has always been the progeny of Raymond K. McLain, but the group has expanded and contracted over the years.  Some members have worked on their own projects when the family band wasn't touring; at least a half-dozen albums attest to that.\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\nDr. Raymond Francis McLain ({{Birth based on age at death|76|1981|05|02}}{{spaced en dash}}May 2, 1981) was president of [[Eureka College]], [[Transylvania University]], and [[The American University in Cairo]] during his career in academia,<ref name=\"1981-05-04 Tuscaloosa News\" /> while his wife Beatrice \"Bicky\" Kane McLain (1906\u20132004)<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" /> was the director of the Center for Southern Regional Folklife Studies at the [[University of Alabama]] from 1966\u20131976.<ref name=\"2004-04-16 Tuscaloosa News\" />  Raymond Francis and Bicky had two children: daughter Rosemary (a \"[[singer-songwriter|singer/songwriter]] and artistic pioneer in the [[rubber stamp]]ing industry\"),<ref name=\"1981-05-04 Tuscaloosa News\" /><ref name=\"2004-04-16 Tuscaloosa News\" /> and son Raymond Kane McLain (1928\u20132003).<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" />\n\nRaymond Kane combined the passions of his parents; he majored in [[music theory]] at [[Denison University]] and did graduate work in [[folk music]] studies at [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of North Carolina]] before moving to [[Hindman, Kentucky]] in 1954 where he became the director of [[Hindman Settlement School]].  While at Hindman, Raymond Kane developed an interest in [[bluegrass music]]; he introduced his three eldest children\u2014Raymond Winslow, Alice, and Ruth\u2014to the genre, and the four of them began playing together.<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\nRaymond Kane married Betty Winslow in 1952,<ref name=\"2017-09 MFB:50YOM ch0\" /> and founded the band at her encouragement in 1968.<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" /><ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\" />  Performing under the name Bluegrass State,<ref name=\"2011 Crowe on the Banjo: CH6\" /> the [[quartet]] initially performed on a weekly [[WYMT-TV#History|WKYH-TV]] [[television show]] for two years.<ref name=\"2017-09 MFB:50YOM ch0\" />  On December 31, 1968, the family's Hindman home burned to the ground; all seven family members and their instruments survived,<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" /> and in 1970, the family moved to [[Berea, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\n===Performing===\n<!-- domestically -->The band performed in all 50 [[U.S. state]]s, and particularly in [[Alaska]] during the winters where \"people really needed music.\"<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" />  Stateside, the band also stood before audiences at the [[Speed Art Museum]], [[Carnegie Hall]], the [[1982 World's Fair]],<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" /> the [[Lincoln Center]]<ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\" />, the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] (at least six times),<ref name=\"1979-04-25 The Daily News\" /> and the [[Carter Family Fold]] (since 1974).<ref name=\"2013-06-05 Cybergrass\" />  They also appeared on the ''[[CBS Morning News]]'', the ''[[Grand Ole Opry]]'', ''[[Hee Haw]]'', [[The Johnny Cash Show (TV series)|''The Johnny Cash Show'']], [[Crook & Chase|''Music City Tonight'']], ''[[Nashville Now]]'', [[Today (American TV program)|''Today'']],<ref name=\"2007-09-23 Tuba Bach Chamber Music Festival\" /> and their own weekly program on [[WKYT-TV]].<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\n<!-- internationally -->After the McLain Family Band played for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]]' music committee in 1972,<ref name=\"2012-11-09 UKY\" /> [[Gian Carlo Menotti]] was so \"charmed by the band\" that he invited them to that year's ''[[Festival dei Due Mondi]]'' in [[Spoleto]], [[Italy]].<ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\" />  That July, the band undertook their first international [[concert tour]] sponsored by the [[United States Department of State]], traveling to Italy, [[West Germany]], and [[Belgium]].<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />  The band made 14 overseas tours\u2014including an \"around-the-world odyssey in 1975\", and performed in 63 different countries.<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" />\n\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}<!-- alphabetically-listed -->\n{{plainlist|\n* {{flag|Afghanistan|1974}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Austria}} (1974)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|Belgium}} (1972)<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n* {{flag|Bolivia}} (1976)<ref name=\"1976-03-03 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Brazil|1968}} (1976)<ref name=\"1976-03-10 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Burma|1974}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Cameroon<!-- needs date -->}}<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|Canada}}<ref name=\"Americana Rhythm\" />\n* {{flag|Chad}}<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|Chile}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Colombia}} (1976)<ref name=\"1976-02-25 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Czechoslovakia}} (1975)<ref name=\"1975-06-17 NPR\" />\n* {{flag|Denmark}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018-11-14 Kingsport Times-News\" />\n* {{flag|Ecuador}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Egypt|1972}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Finland}} (1974)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|France}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|West Germany}} (1972)<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n* {{flag|Guatemala}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Haiti|1964}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Hungary}} (1974 & 75)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /><ref name=\"1975-06-02 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Iceland}} (1974)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|India}} (1975)<ref name=\"1975-05-22 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Indonesia}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-11 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Iran|1964}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Ireland}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018-11-14 Kingsport Times-News\" />\n* {{flag|Italy}} (1972)<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n* {{flag|Japan}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Laos|1952}} (1975)<ref name=\"1975-04-22 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Lebanon}} (1975)<ref name=\"1975-03-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Mexico}}<ref name=\"Americana Rhythm\" />\n* {{flag|Nepal}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Norway}} (1974)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|Paraguay|1954}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Peru}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Philippines|1936}} (1975)<ref name=\"1975-04-15 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Poland|1928}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Romania|1965}} (1974 & 75)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /><ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Spain}} (1974)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|Suriname}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Sweden}} (1974)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n* {{flag|Taiwan}}<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" />\n* {{flag|Tunisia|1959}} (1975)<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Uruguay}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|Venezuela|1954}} (1976)<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\" />\n* {{flag|North Yemen}}<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" />\n* {{flag|Yugoslavia}}<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" />\n}} {{div col end}}\n\nThe band stopped extensively touring in 1990 to allow Raymond Winslow, Alice and Al, and Ruth to personally rear their children without being on the road for months at a time.  In 2018, for their 50th anniversary, the band toured widely again through the US and Europe.<ref name=\"2018-11-14 Kingsport Times-News\" />\n\n===Festival===\n{{Infobox music festival\n| name         = McLain Family Band Festival\n| image        = \n| image_size   = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| genre        = [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]]\n| location     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Renfro Valley, Kentucky|Renfro Valley, KY]], US (1978)\n* [[Bighill, Kentucky|Bighill, KY]], US (1979\u20131987) }}\n| years_active = 1978\u20131987\n| founders     = Raymond Kane McLain\n| attendance   = 6,000\u20137,000 annually\n}}\nRaymond Kane had envisioned for years a [[family-friendly]] bluegrass festival dedicated to performing family groups, and in 1978 he found a {{convert|73|acre|adj=on}} [[farm]] on [[U.S. Route 421]]<ref name=\"1984-09-04 Daily News\" /> in [[Bighill, Kentucky]] that perfectly met the needs of such a festival: \"I found this farm with this marvelous hill forming a natural [[amphitheatre|amphitheater]].  At the bottom of the hill is a grove of [[locust tree|locust]], [[Prunus americana|wild plum]] and [[oak]] trees, a great backdrop for the stage.  The rest is history.\"  That year, the band hosted the inaugural McLain Family Band Festival<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" /> in [[Renfro Valley, Kentucky]], but all subsequent festivals were held on the farm.<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\nThe festival showcased both domestic (including [[Patsy Montana]],<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" /> [[The Whites]], [[Jim & Jesse]], [[Janette Carter]], and the [[Osborne Brothers]]) and international talent (including the Appleseeds from [[Japan]], the Nuyens Family from [[Belgium]], and Fesaci from [[Czechoslovakia]]).<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  Some years, the festival's performers were broadcast on [[NPR]] and [[Kentucky Educational Television]].  Between 6,000\u20137,000 people attended the festival each year,<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" /> many of whom camped on the McLain's farm for the duration.  No [[alcoholic drink]]s or [[illegal drug]]s were allowed on the premises.  In 1987, the entrance fee was {{US$|10|1987}}; the festival ran for three days from 12\u201311{{spaces}}p.m.,<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" /> and ultimately lasted for ten years.<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n\n==McLain music==\nWhile Raymond Kane was [[classically trained]], his children were taught and learned to play by ear.  The band watched videos of their performances to find weaknesses and continually improve: {{nowrap|\"[Raymond Kane]}} said that we should be able to play a piece three consecutive times with no mistakes if it was ready to perform.\"<ref name=\"2018-11-14 Kingsport Times-News\" />\n\nThe McLain Family Band's music has been reviewed as being {{\"'}}cheery,' 'light,' and 'wholesome{{'\"}}, and lacking the painful, \"dark and haunted side of [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]]\".<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  [[George Vecsey]] noted in 1975 that {{nowrap|\"[u]nlike}} many bands, the McLains do little talking, and they minimize their fancy solos.\"<ref name=\"1975-08-23 St. Petersburg Times\" />  The band performs music of their own composition, as well as \"bluegrass and [[country music|country]] [[standard (music)|standards]], [[novelty song]]s, and eastern [[Music of Kentucky|Kentucky traditional music]].\"<ref name=\"1979-04-25 The Daily News\" />  Many of their songs are written by Raymond Kane's sister, Rosemary.<ref name=\"1975-08-23 St. Petersburg Times\" />  The McLain Family Band also played with [[symphonic orchestra]]s, presenting pieces arranged by Phillip Rhodes, [[Newton Wayland]],<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" /> and [[P. D. Q. Bach]] (the fictional alter-ego of [[Peter Schickele]]).<ref name=\"1985-01-06 WAPO\" />  All band members sing both [[lead vocalist|lead]] and [[harmony]].<ref name=\"1979-04-25 The Daily News\" />\n\nIn the late 1970s, the McLain Family Band pioneered combining [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[classical music]],<ref name=\"2004 Homegrown Music: CH4\" /> the first bluegrass band to do so.<ref name=\"2007-04-04 Elizabethton Star\" /><ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />  In 1973, [[composer]] [[Phillip Rhodes (composer)|Phillip Rhodes]] wrote ''Concerto for Bluegrass Band and Orchestra'' for the McLain Family Band,<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> the first \"major work ever written for a bluegrass band and symphony orchestra.\"<ref name=\"2007-04-04 Elizabethton Star\" />  The McLain Family Band has performed it \"hundreds of times with orchestras from all over the [United States].\"<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  Rhodes also composed orchestral [[arrangement]]s of original McLain Family Band songs under a [[commission (art)|commission]] by the [[Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"2007-04-04 Elizabethton Star\" />\n\nOne of the band's most-requested pieces is \"Kentucky Wind\", a song written by Raymonds K. and W. while [[homesickness|homesick]] during a South American tour.  Another is \"Troublesome Creek\", by Raymond W. about a waterway in Hindman; the song is like the creek, \"sometimes, it is a placid stream, a place to catch tadpoles and crayfish. But other times, it is troublesome, a rising torrent threatening to flood houses.\"<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" />\n\nOver the years, the McLain Family Band has repeatedly said that they play because they enjoy doing it.  Raymond Kane once said, \"People pay us to leave our homes, to ride in a van for hours, to set up our instruments\u2026but they don't pay us to play music.  We do that for fun.  The minute we stop enjoying that, we'll do something else.\"<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n\n===Discography===\n[[File:MFB logo.png|thumb|Logo for McLain Family Band albums and ancillary materials]]\nUnder their own label (Country Life Records),<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> the McLain Family Band released 14 [[LP record]]s.<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\n<!-- 4 -->{{discography list\n | Type           = Studio\n | Name           = On the Road<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n | Released       = 1976<ref name=\"MFB Vintage Recordings\" />\n | Format         = [[LP record]]\n | Label          = Country Life\n | Tracks         = \"New River Train\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Old Maid Song\" (McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Lonesome Day\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Pretty Little Reckless Boy\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"If You're Ever Gonna Love Me\" (Buck Graves and Leroy Mack){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"A Heavenly Song\" (McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"On the Road\" (McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Jump Josie\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Believe Me\" (McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Brown Eyed Baby\" (Stovall){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Big River Blues\" ([[The Delmore Brothers|Delmore]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Can't We Get Together Once Again?\" (McLain)<ref name=\"On the Road\" />\n}}\n<!-- 15 -->{{discography list\n | Type           = Studio\n | Name           = Celebrate Life\n | Released       = {{start date|2016}}<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" />\n | Format         = <!-- \"LP/CD/...\" -->\n | Label          = <!-- \"Name\" or \"[[Name Records|Name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Writer         = <!-- \"Songwriter name\" or \"[[Songwriter name]]\" -->\n | Writers        = <!-- Use if there are multiple writers, comma if many -->\n | Producer       = <!-- \"Producer name\" or \"[[Producer name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Director       = <!-- \"Director name\" or \"[[Director name]]\" for music videos -->\n | Chart position = <!-- \"No. 1 U.S.\" or \"No. 12 UK\" or such -->\n | Sales          = <!-- \"3 million sold as of 2005\" or such -->\n | Certification  = <!-- \"Gold\" or such -->\n | Tracks         = <!-- \" \"One\", \"Two\", \"Three\" \", etc. -->\n | Bonus tracks   = <!-- \"Four\" (Japan edition) -->\n | Singles        = <!-- \" \"Single\", \"Other Single\" \", etc. -->\n}}\n\n==Members==\nThe initial four members of the McLain Family Band were Raymond Kane and his first three children: Raymond Winslow, Alice, and Ruth.<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" />  Over the years, band membership expanded to include Raymond Kane's youngest two children Nancy Ann and Michael, Alice's husband Al White, and Ruth's husband Michael Riopel.  At times, the group also featured Raymond Winslow's wife Beverly Buchanan and non-relative Tom Owen.<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />  Raymond Kane's wife, and mother of the five McLain children\u2014Betty\u2014was the band's [[business manager|business]] and [[talent manager]].<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" /><ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\n{{as of|2018|12}}, the McLain Family Band lineup included Raymond Winslow McLain, Alice McLain and Al White, Ruth McLain Smith, and Daxson Lewis, occasionally joined by Nancy Ann Wartman, Michael McLain, and Jennifer McLain.<ref name=\"2018-12-13 Herald-Dispatch\" />\n\n===Raymond Kane and Betty===\n[[File:Mclainsatfold02 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Raymond Kane (second from left) performing with the band at the Carter Fold on September 28, 2002]]\nRaymond Kane McLain was born on April 18, 1928 in [[Alliance, Ohio]].<ref name=\"2012-11-09 UKY\" />  In 1970, Raymond Kane began teaching the United States' first [[university]]-level courses in [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[Appalachian music]] at [[Berea College]].<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />  Raymond Kane McLain was the [[bandleader]] of the group for 20 years.<ref name=\"2004 Homegrown Music: CH8\" />  He [[singing|sang]]<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" /> and played the [[guitar]] and [[accordion]].<ref name=\"1979-04-25 The Daily News\" />  Raymond Kane also wrote music; the ''[[Elizabethton Star]]'' called his [[arrangement]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s second [[Brandenburg Concertos|Brandenburg Concerto]] \"the most stunning\" of his [[musical composition]]s for the band.<ref name=\"2007-04-04 Elizabethton Star\" />  After the band stopped touring in 1989, Raymond Kane became a [[librarian]].<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  He died in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] on February 14, 2003 at 74 years old.<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" />\n\nMary Elizabeth \"Betty\" Winslow<ref name=\"2017-09 MFB:50YOM ch0\" /> (1928\u20132011) had a degree in [[psychology]] from [[Oberlin College]], and married Raymond Kane in 1952.  After they moved to [[Hindman, Kentucky]], she became the recreation director of the [[Hindman Settlement School]].<ref name=\"2011 Lakes Funeral Home\" />  It was with her encouragement that Raymond Kane started the family band in 1968.<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" />  For \"over 20 years\" she managed the band full-time<ref name=\"2011 Lakes Funeral Home\" />\u2014acting as [[talent manager]] and [[bookkeeping|bookkeeper]] at home in [[Berea, Kentucky]] while the band toured<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\u2014and also hosted the band's annual [[Bighill, Kentucky]] [[list of bluegrass music festivals|bluegrass festival]].  She taught English [[country dance]], and was an executive field director for the [[scouting in Kentucky#Girl Scouts of Kentucky's Wilderness Road Council|Wilderness Road Girl Scout Council]].  She was married to Bill Tallmadge from 1999 until his death in 2004.<ref name=\"2011 Lakes Funeral Home\" />\n\n===Raymond Winslow===\nRaymond Winslow McLain was born in 1953.<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  He enrolled at [[Berea College]] when the family moved there in 1970,<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" /> and married Beverly Buchanan in December 1979.<ref name=\"1980-02-01 Sarasota Herald-Tribune\" />  In 2000, Raymond Winslow was made the director of the Bluegrass and Country Music Program at [[East Tennessee State University]].<ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\" /><ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  {{As of|2017}}, he was the [[executive director]] of [[Morehead State University]]'s Kentucky Center for Traditional Music.<ref name=\"2017-09 MFB:50YOM ch0\" />\n\n<!-- w/MFB -->A high [[tenor]]<ref name=\"1982-04-29 NYT\" /> playing [[clawhammer]] [[banjo]],<ref name=\"2004 Homegrown Music: CH5\" /> and [[fiddle]], Raymond Winslow is the most well-known of the McLain family outside of the band,<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" /> and one of \"the most well-traveled musicians in his field\".<ref name=\"Morehead State University: RWM biography\" />  Playing with the family band, Raymond Winslow \"took nearly all the [[lead break]]s in their early years.\"<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  He was a \"musical ambassador\" for the [[United States Department of State]], and made more than 230 appearances with [[orchestra]]s.<ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\" />  Paul Jenkins of ''[[Bluegrass Unlimited]]'' called Raymond Winslow's playing [[virtuoso|virtuosic]],<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> and in 1972, he won a [[Bluegrass Music Award]].<ref name=\"1973-08-26 Tuscaloosa News\" />\n\n<!-- independently -->After the family band stopped touring in 1989, Raymond Winslow joined [[Jim & Jesse]] and played with them for 10 years.<ref name=\"Symphony of the Mountains\" />  During those ten years, he also released two albums of his own: ''A Place of My Own'' (1992) and ''Kentucky Mountain Banjo'' (1995).  Since then, he's also played with \"[[Canadians|Canadian]] [[harmonica]] virtuoso\" [[Mike Stevens (bluegrass harmonica)|Mike Stevens]].<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n\n{{Discography list\n | Type           = Studio\n | Name           = A Place of My Own\n | Other info     = <!-- added between parentheses after Name (album or EP) -->\n | Released       = {{start date|1992}}\n | Format         = [[Cassette tape]],<ref name=\"AllMusic: A Place of My Own: Releases\" /> [[compact disc]]<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n | Label          = Flying Fish\n | Writer         = <!-- \"Songwriter name\" or \"[[Songwriter name]]\" -->\n | Writers        = <!-- Use if there are multiple writers, comma if many -->\n | Producer       = <!-- \"Producer name\" or \"[[Producer name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Director       = <!-- \"Director name\" or \"[[Director name]]\" for music videos -->\n | Chart position = <!-- \"No. 1 U.S.\" or \"No. 12 UK\" or such -->\n | Sales          = <!-- \"3 million sold as of 2005\" or such -->\n | Certification  = <!-- \"Gold\" or such -->\n | Tracks         = \"On the Road\" (Raymond W. McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"A Place of My Own\" (Michael and Raymond W. McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[Cotton-Eyed Joe|Cotton Eyed Joe]]\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Silver Creek\" (Raymond W. McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Windswept\" (Raymond W. McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Wild Fiddler's Rag\" ([[Howdy Forrester|Howard Forrester]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[The Bells of St. Mary's (song)|The Bells of St. Mary's]]\"{{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Raymond's Breakdown\" (Raymond W. McLain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Cannon Ball Blues\" ([[A. P. Carter]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Kitten on the Keys\" ([[Zez Confrey]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Ain't Gonna Work Tomorrow\" ([[Charlie Louvin|Charlie]] and [[Ira Louvin]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Shuckin' the Corn\" (Buck Graves, Gladys Stacey, and Louise Certain){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[Maiden's Prayer]]\" (James and [[Bob Wills]])<ref name=\"AllMusic: A Place of My Own: Overview\" />\n | Bonus tracks   = <!-- \"Four\" (Japan edition) -->\n | Singles        = <!-- \" \"Single\", \"Other Single\" \", etc. -->\n}}{{Discography list\n | Type           = Studio\n | Name           = Kentucky Mountain Banjo\n | Other info     = <!-- added between parentheses after Name (album or EP) -->\n | Released       = {{start date|1995}}\n | Format         = [[Compact disc]]<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n | Label          = <!-- \"Name\" or \"[[Name Records|Name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Writer         = <!-- \"Songwriter name\" or \"[[Songwriter name]]\" -->\n | Writers        = <!-- Use if there are multiple writers, comma if many -->\n | Producer       = <!-- \"Producer name\" or \"[[Producer name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Director       = <!-- \"Director name\" or \"[[Director name]]\" for music videos -->\n | Chart position = <!-- \"No. 1 U.S.\" or \"No. 12 UK\" or such -->\n | Sales          = <!-- \"3 million sold as of 2005\" or such -->\n | Certification  = <!-- \"Gold\" or such -->\n | Tracks         = <!-- \" \"One\", \"Two\", \"Three\" \", etc. -->\n | Bonus tracks   = <!-- \"Four\" (Japan edition) -->\n | Singles        = <!-- \" \"Single\", \"Other Single\" \", etc. -->\n}}\n\n===Alice and Al White===\n[[File:McLain Family Band, 2014 Festival of Faiths (14365733808) (Alice & Al crop).jpg|thumb|Al (left) and Alice White in 2014]]\nAlice McLain White (b. Rose Alice McLain<ref name=\"1975-02-27 USDOS\" /> in 1956) [[singing|sings]], and plays [[mandolin]] and [[double bass]].<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />  She enrolled at [[Berea College]] when the family moved there in 1970.<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />  She met her husband Al on the ''[[Grand Ole Opry]]'' before they married in 1977.<ref name=\"2018-11-14 Kingsport Times-News\" />  Al White (b. 1952)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> grew up playing music in [[New Mexico]], and moved to [[Louisville, Kentucky]] to join the band [[Bluegrass Alliance]].  Al joined the McLain Family Band after marrying Alice;<ref name=\"2013-03-14 Richmond Register\" /> he plays mandolin and [[guitar]],<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" /> and sings.<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />\n\nWhen the McLain Family Band stopped performing in 1989, Alice and Al remained in [[Berea, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"2013-03-14 Richmond Register\" />  There, {{as of|2017|lc=yes}}, Alice was an [[first grade#United States|first-grade]] [[teacher]], Al taught traditional instrument instruction at Berea College,<ref name=\"2017-09 MFB:50YOM ch0\" /> and the two of them played concerts and for [[folk dance|folk]] and [[contra dance|contra dancing]].<ref name=\"2013-03-14 Richmond Register\" />\n\n===Ruth, Nancy Ann, and Michael===\n[[File:Ruth McLain Smith (2010-10-08).jpg|thumb|left|Ruth McLain Smith at the [[Museum of Appalachia]] in [[Norris, Tennessee|Norris, TN]] (2010)]]\nRuth McLain Smith (b. Ruth Helen McLain<ref name=\"1975-02-27 USDOS\" /> in 1958)<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> plays [[mandolin]], [[double bass]], and [[singing|sings]].<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />  When the band formed in 1968, she stood on chairs and [[milk crate]]s to reach the [[neck (music)|neck]] of her bass.<ref name=\"2015-12-19 The Daily Independent\" />  As a child, Ruth played the [[Appalachian dulcimer]] at the [[White House]] on national television after only two weeks of learning the instrument.<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" />  In 2007, Ruth was playing regularly with [[Grandpa Jones]]' family, and was a director with [[Usborne Publishing]].<ref name=\"2007-09-23 Tuba Bach Chamber Music Festival\" />  Ruth has a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Berea College]], and {{as of|2016|lc=yes}} was a [[lecturer]] at [[Morehead State University]].<ref name=\"Morehead State University: RMS biography\" />  Prior to 2007, Ruth married Philip Smith, and they have four children.<ref name=\"2007-09-23 Tuba Bach Chamber Music Festival\" />  In 2011, she moved back to [[Berea, Kentucky]] to care for her mother, Betty.<ref name=\"2013-03-14 Richmond Register\" />\n\nNancy Ann McLain Wartman was born in 1965,<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> had joined the band by 1979,<ref name=\"1979-04-25 The Daily News\" /> and performs on double bass, mandolin, and vocals.<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />  Nancy Ann joined up with [[Usborne Publishing]] in 1994 and held the position of director within the company {{as of|2016|09|lc=yes}}.<ref name=\"Usborne Books & More\" /><ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n\nMichael, who was born in 1967,<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" /> plays [[banjo]], guitar,<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" /> and mandolin.<ref name=\"1982-07-23 Advocate-Messenger\" />  He has played with the [[Claire Lynch|Claire Lynch Band]] and [[Dale Ann Bradley]],<ref name=\"Americana Rhythm\" /> and he married his wife Jennifer a week after [[marriage proposal|proposing]] atop the [[Crowne Plaza]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"Banjocats: Milestones\" />  {{As of|2014|04}}, Michael taught bluegrass and traditional instruments at [[Belmont University]].<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n\n===Others===\nTom Owen had joined the band by 1979, and played [[banjo]], [[guitar]], and [[mandolin]].<ref name=\"1979-04-25 The Daily News\" />  He was not related to the McLains.<ref name=\"Berea College: MFB Records Guide\" />\n\nA band member by May 1981,<ref name=\"2005 From Every Stage\" /> Michael Riopel (b. {{birth based on age as of date|27|1982|07|23|noage=1}}) married Ruth and played [[guitar]], mandolin, and [[harmonica]].<ref name=\"1982-07-23 Advocate-Messenger\" />\n\nRaymond Kane's mother, Beatrice \"Bicky\" Kane McLain (1906\u20132004)<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" />\u2014called \"the [[matriarch]] of the band\" by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\u2014had joined the band by 1987<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" /> and traveled with them for the better part of twelve years<ref name=\"2004-04-16 Tuscaloosa News\" /> singing traditional [[ballad]]s such as the 17th century [[murder ballad]] \"[[The Twa Sisters|Two Sisters]]\".<ref name=\"1987-08-23 LAT\" />  Bicky died on April 3, 2004 in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]].<ref name=\"AllMusic: McLain Family Band\" /><ref name=\"2004-04-16 Tuscaloosa News\" />\n\n==Associated acts==\nShortly after Michael and Jennifer McLain married, they joined with Raymond Winslow to form \"The McLains\".<ref name=\"Banjocats: Milestones\" />  In 1999, The McLains released their only album, ''More Fun Than We Ought to Have''<ref name=\"AllMusic: More Fun Than We Ought to Have\" /> ([[Pinecastle Records]]).<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />  Michael and Jennifer later became the \"Michael and Jennifer McLain Band\", appending that with \"featuring Dan Kelly\" when the eponymous [[fiddle]]r joined their group.<ref name=\"Banjocats: Milestones\" />  They released ''Hit the Road and Go'' on November 4, 2016.<ref name=\"Americana Rhythm\" />\n\nWhen Ruth returned to Berea in 2011, she and the Whites formed \"Al, Alice & Ruth\".  They play \"upbeat, [[Appalachia|Appalachian]]-flavored [[bluegrass music]] [\u2026 on the] [[banjo]], [[fiddle]], [[mandolin]], [[guitar]] and [[double bass|bass]].\"  In March 2013, Al, Alice & Ruth released their first album, ''Let the Mountains Roll''.<ref name=\"2013-03-14 Richmond Register\" /><ref name=\"Al, Alice and Ruth: About\" />  Their second album, a [[Christmas music|Christmas album]] titled ''{{'}}Tis a Gift'', was released December 2014.<ref name=\"Al, Alice and Ruth: About\" />\n\n{{Discography list\n | Type           = Studio\n | Name           = Let the Mountains Roll\n | Other info     = <!-- added between parentheses after Name (album or EP) -->\n | Released       = {{start date|2013|03}}\n | Format         = [[Compact disc]]\n | Label          = Al, Alice & Ruth<ref name=\"AllMusic: Let the Mountains Roll: Releases\" />\n | Writer         = <!-- \"Songwriter name\" or \"[[Songwriter name]]\" -->\n | Writers        = <!-- Use if there are multiple writers, comma if many -->\n | Producer       = <!-- \"Producer name\" or \"[[Producer name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Director       = <!-- \"Director name\" or \"[[Director name]]\" for music videos -->\n | Chart position = <!-- \"No. 1 U.S.\" or \"No. 12 UK\" or such -->\n | Sales          = <!-- \"3 million sold as of 2005\" or such -->\n | Certification  = <!-- \"Gold\" or such -->\n | Tracks         = \"When the Storm Is Over\" ([[Robert Lucas (musician)|Robert Lucas]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Cool of the Day\" ([[Jean Ritchie|Jean Ritchie Pickow]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Dancing with the Angels\" ([[Peter Rowan]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Foreign Lander\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"My Lazy Day\" ([[Smiley Burnette]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Killy Kranky\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[What Wondrous Love Is This|Wondrous Love]]\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Green, Green Rocky Road\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[Polly Put the Kettle On]]\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[Palms of Victory|Pans of Biscuits]]\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Angel Gabriel\" (Traditional){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"Let the Mountains Roll\" ([[Billy Edd Wheeler]]){{spaces}}&#183;{{spaces}}\"[[Shady Grove (song)|Shady Grove]]\" (Traditional)<ref name=\"AllMusic: Let the Mountains Roll: Overview\" />\n | Bonus tracks   = <!-- \"Four\" (Japan edition) -->\n | Singles        = <!-- \" \"Single\", \"Other Single\" \", etc. -->\n}}\n{{Discography list\n | Type           = Studio\n | Name           = 'Tis a Gift\n | Other info     = <!-- added between parentheses after Name (album or EP) -->\n | Released       = {{start date|2014|12}}\n | Format         = [[Compact disc]]<ref name=\"Al, Alice and Ruth: About\" />\n | Label          = <!-- \"Name\" or \"[[Name Records|Name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Writer         = <!-- \"Songwriter name\" or \"[[Songwriter name]]\" -->\n | Writers        = <!-- Use if there are multiple writers, comma if many -->\n | Producer       = <!-- \"Producer name\" or \"[[Producer name]]\", comma if many -->\n | Director       = <!-- \"Director name\" or \"[[Director name]]\" for music videos -->\n | Chart position = <!-- \"No. 1 U.S.\" or \"No. 12 UK\" or such -->\n | Sales          = <!-- \"3 million sold as of 2005\" or such -->\n | Certification  = <!-- \"Gold\" or such -->\n | Tracks         = <!-- \" \"One\", \"Two\", \"Three\" \", etc. -->\n | Bonus tracks   = <!-- \"Four\" (Japan edition) -->\n | Singles        = <!-- \" \"Single\", \"Other Single\" \", etc. -->\n}}\n\n==Reception and recognition==\nIn his review of the band's 1982 performance at [[Carnegie Hall]], [[Robert Palmer (writer)|Robert Palmer]] described the combination of traditional [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and \"archaic modal harmonies\" as slick and modern.  Ultimately, while Palmer called out the amateur qualities of the family's performance, \"they performed an attractive mixture of old favorites and originals, and their instrumental and especially their vocal arrangements were consistently fresh.\"<ref name=\"1982-04-29 NYT\" />  ''[[The Pittsburgh Press]]'' called a McLain Family Band performance \"full of open-hearted earnestness, wholesomeness and energy.\"<ref name=\"2000-11-14 ETSU\" />\n\n[[Michael Johnathon]] of ''[[WoodSongs Old-Time Radio Hour]]'' called the McLain Family Band \"musically[,] one of the best bluegrass bands of all times.\"  Johnathon also said of the band, \"They took what [[Bill Monroe]] did and put their own Kentucky stamp on it.  They brought in textures of [[classical music]] and made the song and presentation more important than any one lead.  They infused a youthful energy and musical depth, creating their own legacy.\"<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  In 2013, the McLain Family Band received a Distinguished Achievement Award from the [[International Bluegrass Music Association]].<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />  [[Sharon White (singer)|Sharon White]] said in 2018, \"It is impossible to measure the influence this family band has had on the bluegrass music world. They continue to inspire and mentor future bluegrass musicians through their work in schools and universities.\"<ref name=\"2018-10-01 Kentucky Monthly\" />\n\n===Outside the US===\nIn September 1974, [[United States Ambassador to Pakistan]] [[Henry A. Byroade]] sent a [[diplomatic cable]] to the [[United States Department of State]] asking for a [[National Endowment for the Arts]] (NEA) evaluation of [[Hellman's Angels]] and the McLain Family Band for possibly booking concerts in [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"1974-09-04 USDOS\" />  The State Department acquired a review by an NEA panel member, replying, \"McLain Family Band is pleasantly amateurish, however, their enthusiasm and spirit make up for their lack of polish and on this basis he would give a 'good' rating.\"<ref name=\"1974-09-14 USDOS\" />\n\nAfter their April 11\u201314, 1975 performances in Manila,<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" /> [[United States Ambassador to the Philippines]] [[William H. Sullivan]] reported that the McLain Family Band \"performed five times in [[Manila]] with excellent results, generating much enthusiasm among university students, professional musicians, and the public.  [\u2026]  By every indication, McLain's '[[bluegrass music]]' seems very welcome expression of [[Americana]] here; it helped dispel notion that [[Kentucky]] means only '[[KFC|fried chicken]]'.  [\u2026]  They establish wholesome, happy mood with audience, {{sic|redily}} improvise, are each professionally expert\".<ref name=\"1975-04-15 USDOS\" />  Similarly, after performing in [[Laos]] from April 19\u201323 that same year,<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" /> the United States [[diplomatic mission]] in [[Vientiane]] gave \"high praise of McLain Band performances.  {{sic|McLain's}} convey dramatically the joy of 'bluegrass music' and evoke enthusiastic audience response.  {{sic|McLain's}} are outstanding musicians who represent the finest in [[culture of the United States|American traditions]].  Seldom in experience of all officers at post have we programmed a more cooperative, congenial and talented group.\"<ref name=\"1975-04-22 USDOS\" />  The McLain Family Band performed in [[Romania]] May 21\u201325, 1975;<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" /> the United States diplomatic mission in [[Bucharest]] had nothing but good things to say about them:\n\n{{quote|text=How can anyone not like the McLain Family Band?  Sincere people and talented musicians they represent the best in American character traits of friendliness, informality and a sincere respect for and curiosity about other cultures while offering their audiences a taste of a unique American musical genre.  [\u2026]  Each audience demanded (and received) more than the standard program with 4 or 5 [[encore]]s becoming the norm.  The variety of the McLain program -- humorous songs blended with religious and regional numbers impressed the listeners with the richness of bluegrass music.  The musical talents and personalities particularly of young Raymond [Winslow] McLain and his sister Ruth provoked continuous applause.  The McLain style is deceptively {{sic|profissional}} without being slick or overtly commercial.  The {{sic|misical}} arrangements are simple and straight-forward but one never doubts the professionalism, the careful timing and pacing of the program.  Audiences included [[classical music]] [[composer]]s, journalists, theatre personalities and, in large numbers, young students.  The unanimous reaction was positive with several people asking specifically that the McLains return to Bucharest for a third time.  The McLains already have many commitments for 1976 but if they are available for a European tour the post requests a one-week program which will allow provincial city visits.|author=United States embassy in Bucharest<ref name=\"1975-05-28 USDOS\" />}}\n\nHigh praise came from [[United States Ambassador to Hungary]] [[Eugene V. McAuliffe]] after the band played there from May 25\u201330, 1975.<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\" />\n\n{{quote|text=Without doubt the McLain Family Band is the most {{sic|senstational}}, attractive and effective cultural presentation which could possibly be fielded by the {{bracket|[[United States Government]]}} in support of its goal of projecting the best and most favorable image of the U.S. to any audience, in any country, {{sic|anwhere}}.  Musically the McLains are first rate.  Personally they radiate enthusiasm, simplicity, love of people, love of music.  Their art form is little known, but it tells a lot of a side of American which {{sic|usuually}} little known.  They have universal appeal and can charm any audience into foot-stomping, thunderous applause.  They are simply the best there is.  [\u2026]  [[Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs|CU/ARTS]] could never find any better use of its funds than keeping this group on the road every year for as long as possible to as many countries as possible, and particularly in 1976.|author=McAuliffe<ref name=\"1975-06-02 USDOS\" />}}\n\nSpeaking on their performance in [[Czechoslovakia]], Raymond Kane said, \"It's one thing to say the trip was a success, but that really doesn't tell what we saw and felt.  The [[Czechs]] were so overwhelmed that they came up to us and touched our faces and [[crying|cried]].\"<ref name=\"2014-04 Bluegrass Unlimited\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n\n<!-- dated sources sorted chronologically -->\n\n<ref name=\"1973-08-26 Tuscaloosa News\">{{cite news |date=1973-08-26 |title=McLain Concert Slated Wednesday |work=[[The Tuscaloosa News]] |page=11D}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1974-09-04 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Byroade |first=Henry A. |author-link=Henry A. Byroade |date=1974-09-04 |title=CULTURAL PRESENTATIONS: PROFESSIONAL ARTISTS TOURING ABROAD COMMERCIALLY}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1974-09-14 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Kissinger |first=Henry |author-link=Henry Kissinger |date=1974-09-14 |title=PERFORMING ARTS GROUPS TOURING ABROAD PRIVATELY}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1974-12-06 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Kissinger |first=Henry |author-link=Henry Kissinger |date=1974-12-06 |title=CU/ARTS: MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1974-12-11 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Ingersoll |first=Robert S. |author-link=Robert S. Ingersoll |date=1974-12-11 |title=CU/ARTS:MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-02-27 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Kissinger |first=Henry |author-link=Henry Kissinger |date=1975-02-27 |title=MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-03-06 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Ingersoll |first=Robert S. |author-link=Robert S. Ingersoll |date=1975-03-06 |title=CU/ARTS:MCLAIN FAMILY BAND PRIVATE TOUR}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-04-15 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Sullivan |first=William H. |author-link=William H. Sullivan |date=1975-04-15 |title=MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-04-22 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Pate |date=1975-04-22 |title=MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-05-22 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Ingersoll |first=Robert S. |author-link=Robert S. Ingersoll |date=1975-05-22 |title=CU/ARTS - CHARLIE BYRD TRIO; FOLK GROUP}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-05-28 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Viets |date=1975-05-28 |title=MCLAIN FAMILY BAND CONCERTS IN BUCHAREST}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-06-02 USDOS\">{{citation |last=McAuliffe |first=Eugene V. |author-link=Eugene V. McAuliffe |date=1975-06-02 |title=CU/ARTS: CULTURAL PRESENTATIONS: MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-06-17 NPR\">{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Noah |author-link1=Noah Adams |date=1975-06-17 |title=McLain Family Band<!-- placeholder --> |url=https://ondemand.npr.org/anon.npr-mp3/npr/specials/2009/11/20091118_specials_adamsfirstpiece.mp3 |url-status=live |work=[[All Things Considered]] |language=en |publisher=[[NPR]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228010317/https://ondemand.npr.org/anon.npr-mp3/npr/specials/2009/11/20091118_specials_adamsfirstpiece.mp3 |archive-date=2019-12-28 |access-date=2019-12-28 |format=MP3}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1975-08-23 St. Petersburg Times\">{{cite news |last1=Vecsey |first1=George |author-link1=George Vecsey |date=1975-08-23 |title=Family pick of Bluegrass crop |work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]] |page=6B |oclc=5920090}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1975-11-13 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Kissinger |first=Henry |author-link=Henry Kissinger |date=1975-11-13 |title=CU/ARTS: MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1976-02-25 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Kissinger |first=Henry |author-link=Henry Kissinger |date=1976-02-25 |title=CU/ARTS: MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"1976-03-03 USDOS\">{{citation |last=Ingersoll |first=Robert S. |author-link=Robert S. Ingersoll |date=1976-03-03 |title=CU/ARTS: MCLAIN FAMILY BAND}}